"England","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bermingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam, Sinead.","Irish (of English origin): variant of   Birmingham  . This form of the surname is found mainly in Ireland.","History: The Bermingham family take their surname from lands held at what is now a great city in the West Midlands of England, but it was brought to Ireland as early as the 12th century. The Norman baron Robert de Bermyngeham was a follower of Strongbow (see   Clare  ); his name is found on a number of Irish charters between 1175 and 1179. The family was also known as <i>Mac Fheorais</i> (see   Corish  ) in Ireland, named for Piers (Gaelic <i>Feoras</i>) de Bermyngeham, the father of Robert."],"variants":[{"name":"Birmingham","meanings":["English: habitational name from Birmingham in the West Midlands. In Domesday Book the name is already found as <i>Bermingeham</i>, but it seems likely that it was originally <i>Beornmundingahām</i> ‘homestead (Old English <i>hām</i>) of the people of (<i>-inga-</i>) <i>Beornmund</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>beorn</i> ‘young man, warrior’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protection’. This surname is established in Ireland (see   Bermingham  )."]},{"name":"Corish","meanings":["Irish:","shortened form of <i>Mac Fheorais</i> ‘son of Piers’. The name was borne by a Connacht family descended from Piers de Bermingham, second lord of Athenry in Galway (died <i>c.</i> 1309). Compare   Bermingham  .","shortened form of <i>Mac Muirghis</i> ‘son of <i>Maurice</i>’, a personal name introduced to Ireland by the Normans. Compare   Morrissey  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":6,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705184,"age":16,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705185,"age":26,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"William de Bermingham was born in 1080, in England. He had at least 1 son with Isobel de Bernigham. He died in 1132, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1080–1132":"1080–1132","1078–1138":"1078–1138","1104–1164":"1104–1164","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1138":"1138","1104":"1104","8 November 1104":"8. november 1104","1078":"1078","1132":"1132","1164":"1164","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","England":"England","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England"},"fi":{"1080–1132":"1080–1132","1078–1138":"1078–1138","1104–1164":"1104–1164","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1138":"1138","1104":"1104","8 November 1104":"8. marraskuuta 1104","1078":"1078","1132":"1132","1164":"1164","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","England":"England","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, England"},"fr":{"1080–1132":"1080–1132","1078–1138":"1078–1138","1104–1164":"1104–1164","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1138":"1138","1104":"1104","8 November 1104":"8 novembre 1104","1078":"1078","1132":"1132","1164":"1164","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","England":"Angleterre","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William de Bermingham est né en 1080, à Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils avec Isobel de Bernigham. Il est décédé en 1132, à l’âge de 52 ans."},"de":{"1080–1132":"1080–1132","1078–1138":"1078–1138","1104–1164":"1104–1164","1080":"1080","1106":"1106","1138":"1138","1104":"1104","8 November 1104":"8. November 1104","1078":"1078","1132":"1132","1164":"1164","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","England":"England","Birmingham, Warwickshire, England":"Birmingham, Warwickshire, Engl